<section class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row pt-10 pb-0 lg:py-10 bg-slate-800">
  <!--Step 1-->
  <div class="flex flex-col items-center lg:w-1/2 p-text text-gray-300">
    <div class="p-10 "><%=image_tag "commercial-step-flying-1.webp", alt: "pilot-on-flight", class: "rounded-lg"%></div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold pb-4 font-sans mx-5 text-center uppercase font-header text-white">Step 1. Start Flight Training</h3>
    <p class="text-base w-3/4 p-text">
      Start your Commercial Certificate Training by pairing up with a CFII. You also need to log a minimum of 250 total flight hours, including 100 hours as pilot-in-command (PIC) and 50 hours of cross-country flight time. Proceed to practical flight training with experienced instructors. This phase refines your piloting skills, focusing on maneuvers, emergency procedures, and various flight scenarios. You'll accumulate the required flight hours, including instrument and complex aircraft training.
    </p>
  </div>
  <!--Step 2-->
  <div class="flex flex-col items-center lg:w-1/2 p-text text-gray-300  lg:h-full">
    <div class="p-10"><%=image_tag "commercial-step-flying-2.webp", alt: "Wingside view of the sky", class: "rounded-lg"%></div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold pb-4 font-sans mx-5 text-center uppercase font-header text-white">Step 2. Pass the Written Exam</h3>
    <p class="text-base w-3/4 p-text">
      Get ready to excel by mastering the subjects covered in the Commercial Pilot Certificate written exam. Delve into aviation regulations, navigation techniques, meteorology, and aircraft systems, showcasing a thorough grasp of commercial flight principles. Acing this exam not only demonstrates your theoretical proficiency but also reinforces your capability to make well-informed decisions during real-world commercial flying scenarios.
    </p>
  </div>
  <!--Step 3-->
  <div class="flex flex-col items-center lg:w-1/2 p-text text-gray-300">
    <div class="p-10 "><%=image_tag "commercial-step-flying-3.webp", alt: "Pilot about to go on a cross country at Ideal Aviation", class: "rounded-lg"%></div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold pb-4 font-sans mx-5 text-center uppercase font-header text-white">Step 3. Complete Long Cross Country</h3>
    <p class="text-base w-3/4">
      Elevate your skills with a pivotal phase: the completion of a demanding long cross-country flight. Covering a minimum distance of 300 nautical miles and touching down at a minimum of three different airports, this journey sharpens your navigation prowess, strategic planning, and cross-country expertise. Guiding you through diverse weather and navigation challenges, this experience equips you with the competence to navigate confidently and safely under real-world commercial conditions, further solidifying your readiness for the Commercial Pilot Certificate.
    </p>
  </div>
  <!--Step 4-->
  <div class="flex flex-col items-center lg:w-1/2 p-text text-gray-300 mb-10 lg:mb-0">
    <div class="p-10"><%=image_tag "commercial-step-check-ride", alt: "An Ideal Aviation student right after passing his checkride", class: "rounded-lg"%></div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold pb-4 font-sans mx-5 text-center uppercase font-header text-white">Step 4. Complete the Commercial Certificate Checkride</h3>
    <p class="text-base w-3/4">
      The culmination of your training is the FAA checkride, consisting of an oral exam and a flight test. A designated FAA examiner evaluates your aeronautical knowledge and flight proficiency. Passing the checkride earns you your Commercial Pilot Certificate, marking a significant achievement in your aviation journey.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
<!--Eligibility Reqs-->
<section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-blue-50 to-blue-200 text-black py-20">
  <div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row items-center justify-center">
    <!--Text-->
    <div class="lg:w-1/2 flex flex-col items-center lg:items-end">
      <!--Container for text to align them-->
      <div class="lg:text-left">
        <h2 class="font-semibold text-2xl lg:text-4xl text-center pb-4">Eligibility Requirements for a Commercial Pilot Certificate</h2>
        <div class="text-base px-6 lg:pl-0 lg:pr-8">
          <p class="pb-5">
            To qualify for an FAA commercial pilot license, individuals need to meet specific criteria. This includes being at least 18 years old and possessing the ability to comprehend and communicate effectively in the English language, encompassing reading, speaking, and writing skills. 
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs mt-4">Reference <a class="text-blue-800 hover:underline" href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-14/chapter-I/subchapter-D/part-61/subpart-F/section-61.123">14 CFR §61.123</a> for the entire list of eligibility requirements.</p>
          <p class="my-2 pb-5 font-semibold text-2xl">
            Requirements:
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside border-b-2 border-slate-300 pb-3 pl-3">
              <li class="mb-2">Holding a current private pilot certificate</li>
              <li class="mb-2">Receiving ground training from an authorized instructor or completing a home study course for aeronautical knowledge</li>
              <li class="mb-2">Logbook Endorsements from an instructor:
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside pl-4 pt-2">
                  <li class="mb-2">Obtain instructor endorsements in your logbook, allowing you to take the aeronautical knowledge test.</li>
                  <li class="mb-2">Secure logbook endorsements to participate in the practical test</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="mb-2">Test Achievements:
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside pl-4 pt-2">
                  <li class="mb-2">Excel in the commercial pilot knowledge test (commonly known as the written exam, abbreviated as CAX)</li>
                  <li class="mb-2">Conquer the commercial pilot practical test, also referred to as the checkride</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          <p class="my-2 pb-5 font-semibold text-2xl">
            Aeronautical Experience & Qualifications</p>
          <p class="my-2 pb-5 font-semibold text-l">In accordance with <a class="text-blue-800 hover:underline" href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-14/chapter-I/subchapter-D/part-61/subpart-F/section-61.129">federal regulations</a>, you need to have documented the specified aeronautical flight experience prerequisites to qualify for a commercial pilot license.</p>
          <p class="my-2 pb-5 font-semibold text-2xl">
            Commercial Pilot Flight Time Requirements:
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside pb-3 pl-3">
              <li class="mb-2">Accumulate a total flight time of at least 250 hours</li>
              <li class="mb-2">Attain a minimum of 100 hours as pilot-in-command (PIC)</li>
              <li class="mb-2">Complete 50 hours of cross-country flight time as PIC</li>
              <li class="mb-2">Obtain 10 hours of dedicated instrument training</li>
              <li class="mb-2">Fulfill 10 hours of flight time in Technically Advanced Aircraft (TAA)</li>
              <p class="text-xs mt-4">Reference <a class="text-blue-800 hover:underline" href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-14/chapter-I/subchapter-D/part-61/subpart-F/section-61.129">14 CFR §61.129</a> for the entire list of eligibility requirements.</p>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
